==Military service and death==
[[File:Operational B.E.2c.jpg|thumb|left|A [[Royal Aircraft Factory B.E.2#B.E.2c|RAF B.E.2c]] of the type which Gallie and Wallace were flying when shot down in August 1915]]
Wallace, who was a cadet of the [[Officers Training Corps]], was commissioned [[second lieutenant]] in the 5th Battalion, [[Rifle Brigade (Prince Consort's Own)|The Rifle Brigade (Prince Consort's Own)]] on 5 August 1914, while still an undergraduate.{{sfn|McCrery|2014|p=214}}<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=28873|date=18 August 1914|startpage=6503|accessdate=21 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=28922|date=2 October 1914|startpage=7816|accessdate=21 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=29278|supp=yes|date=27 August 1915|startpage=8617|accessdate=21 July 1915}}</ref> There were suggestions at the time that he was the first undergraduate to go into action but they were not substantiated.{{sfn|Sewell|1919|p=220}} After two weeks' training at [[Isle of Sheppey|Sheppey]], he departed for France on 30 August. There, he participated in the [[First Battle of the Aisne]] and was active on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] at [[Frelinghien]] and [[Ploegsteert Wood]].{{sfn|Sewell|1919|p=220}}

Wallace was attached to [[No. 2 Squadron RAF|No. 2 Squadron]], 1st Wing [[Royal Flying Corps]] (RFC) on 14 February 1915 as an [[air observer|observer]],{{sfn|Sewell|1919|p=220}} alongside [[William Barnard Rhodes-Moorhouse]], the first serviceman of the RFC to be awarded the [[Victoria Cross]].{{sfn|McCrery|2014|p=214}} By July he was the squadron's senior observer and was made up to [[lieutenant]] on 21 July 1915.{{sfn|Sewell|1919|p=220}}<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=29279|supp=yes|date=27 August 1915|startpage=8631|accessdate=21 July 1915}}</ref> On 22 August 1915, Wallace was on a photographic reconnaissance mission in a [[Royal Aircraft Factory B.E.2#B.E.2c|B.E.2c]] piloted by his friend 2Lt Charles Gallie. The plane was hit by anti-aircraft fire and came straight down at Sainghin, near [[Lille]], northern France.{{sfn|McCrery|2014|p=214}}

Both men were buried near to where they fell, but after the war their bodies were reinterred at the Cabaret-Rouge British Cemetery (Grave reference XII. D. 11), [[Souchez]], near [[Arras]], France.{{sfn|McCrery|2014|p=214}}<ref name=WMWCWGC/>

